        <h2>Where Autodesk Build wins</h2>

        <h3>BIM and 3D model integration</h3>
        <p>Autodesk Build's deepest differentiator is its connection to Autodesk's design tools. If your architect or engineer uses Revit, you can view and navigate the 3D model from the field, link issues directly to model elements, and see design revisions update automatically in the field set. This field-to-BIM loop is increasingly valuable on complex commercial projects where coordination issues are expensive.</p>
        <p>Fieldwire handles 2D drawings extremely well but has limited 3D/BIM capability. For projects where model-based coordination is central, this is a significant gap.</p>

        <h3>Autodesk Construction Cloud ecosystem</h3>
        <p>Autodesk Build is one component of the Autodesk Construction Cloud (ACC), which also includes Autodesk Docs (document management), Autodesk Takeoff, and Autodesk Design Collaboration. Companies already invested in ACC get significant value from keeping everything within the ecosystem — drawings, models, documents, field issues, and RFIs all share a single data environment.</p>

        <h3>Enterprise-grade RFI and issue workflows</h3>
        <p>Autodesk Build's RFI module is more complete than Fieldwire's — configurable routing, response tracking, deadline management, and linkage to affected drawings or model elements. For commercial projects with high RFI volumes, this workflow depth matters. Issue tracking includes custom fields, configurable statuses, and escalation logic that goes beyond what Fieldwire offers.</p>

        <h3>Analytics and project intelligence</h3>
        <p>Autodesk Build connects to the Autodesk Construction Cloud's Insight analytics layer, providing cross-project data on issue trends, productivity metrics, and quality performance. For construction companies trying to improve processes across a project portfolio, this intelligence capability is a genuine advantage.</p>

        <h2>Where Fieldwire wins</h2>

        <h3>Pure field usability</h3>
        <p>Fieldwire's interface is faster, simpler, and more intuitive than Autodesk Build's for frontline field use. Drawing loading is snappy, markup tools are responsive, and task creation from a drawing tap takes seconds. Fieldwire was built from the ground up for field use; Autodesk Build is an enterprise platform with strong field capability.</p>
        <p>In deployments where technology adoption among field crews is a challenge, Fieldwire's lower friction typically results in higher actual usage. The best field management software is the one your team actually uses consistently.</p>

        <h3>Price accessibility</h3>
        <p>Fieldwire's free plan (up to 5 users) and per-user pricing starting around $15-54/month make it accessible for smaller teams, specialty subs, and companies evaluating field management tools before committing to enterprise pricing. Autodesk Build requires a meaningful financial commitment before you can determine whether it fits your workflows.</p>

        <h3>Best-in-class 2D markup tools</h3>
        <p>For 2D plan work specifically, Fieldwire's markup and annotation tools are the best in class. Apple Pencil support, layer management, hyperlinked drawing views, and the ability to create tasks by tapping directly on plan locations are field workflow capabilities that Fieldwire has refined over years of iteration. The experience is better than Autodesk Build's for teams living in 2D drawings.</p>

        <h3>Deployment flexibility</h3>
        <p>Fieldwire can be deployed quickly without organizational alignment with a larger software ecosystem. A superintendent can get their team using Fieldwire within a day. Autodesk Build deployment, particularly when connecting to the broader ACC ecosystem, takes planning and implementation support.</p>

        <h2>Who should choose Autodesk Build?</h2>
        <ul>
          <li>Commercial GCs and owners already using Autodesk Design tools (Revit, AutoCAD)</li>
          <li>Projects with complex BIM coordination requirements</li>
          <li>Companies that want a unified Autodesk Construction Cloud environment</li>
          <li>Teams with dedicated PM staff who manage high RFI and issue volumes</li>
          <li>Organizations with enterprise IT requirements and integration needs</li>
        </ul>

        <div class="cta-box">
          <p><strong>Autodesk Build</strong> — Field-to-BIM connectivity for design-build and commercial teams.</p>
          <a href="https://construction.autodesk.com/products/autodesk-build/" rel="nofollow sponsored" class="btn">Explore Autodesk Build →</a>
        </div>

        <h2>Who should choose Fieldwire?</h2>
        <ul>
          <li>Field teams who need the best 2D drawing and task management tools</li>
          <li>Specialty subcontractors who need accessible field tools without enterprise cost</li>
          <li>Projects where rapid deployment and field adoption are priorities</li>
          <li>Teams that don't need 3D BIM integration or Autodesk ecosystem connectivity</li>
          <li>Any company that wants to start with a free plan before committing</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>The verdict</h2>
        <p>If your project or company is embedded in the Autodesk ecosystem and you need BIM-connected field operations, <strong>Autodesk Build</strong> is the right choice. If you want the best pure field management tool for 2D plan work, task management, and punch lists at an accessible price, <strong>Fieldwire</strong> wins. Many large commercial projects use both — Autodesk Build for the PM and RFI layer, Fieldwire for frontline field operations.</p>

